In this section, the system model used to evaluate the performance of the proposed method is described. This model considers a WSN in which sensor nodes are randomly deployed in a specific environment. The system model comprises a heterogeneous WSN in which each node has different initial energy, buffer capacity, and radio power. The node’s buffer capacity, which is restricted, determines its ability to store input data prior to transmission. This model experiences data packet loss when the buffers of nodes reach their capacity, which negatively affects the network’s performance and poses a challenge for the network’s performance at critical situations. The communication channel between nodes is modeled as a wireless relay channel, effectively describing the propagation conditions of radio waves in realistic environments. Nodes generate their sensed data at a random rate according to a Poisson distribution, which is suitable for modeling the process of generating random data in WSNs and well reflects the independent performance of nodes in sensing. The energy consumption of nodes for data transmission, reception, and processing is determined using a non-linear model, which provides a more accurate representation of actual energy consumption compared to linear models. The energy consumption for transferring N bits of data between two nodes in this architecture is equivalent to38:1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
